										<tr>
											<td width="100%" valign="top">					
												<!-- START NEWS AREAS-->
												<table width="90%" border="0" align="center" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0">
													<tr><td valign="top" width="100%">&nbsp;<br>
													<!-- strMainData goes here-->
													<table align=center cellpadding='3' width='85%'>
  <tr><td bgcolor='black' class='header'>PLAYER JOURNAL</td></tr>  <tr><td ><font class='spti'>13. Clan Crushbone</font> - Brodur</td></tr>
  <tr><td > </td></tr>
  <tr><td ><p> We entered Clan Crushbone territory at night.  Taking the few sleepy guards by surprise from behind (note: it took much coaxing to prod Aventari to slay his enemies from behind) we slipped past the ever burning fires and made our way into the small valley that houses the Crushbone Castle.  </p>
<p> The only constant sounds in this horrid placer were those of whips cracking and slaves crying out.  The rising anger in our three hearts demanded satisfaction, and before venturing towards the castle we waded into the heart of the slave area to free some tortured souls.  Some slaves have obviously lost their minds, as they even aided their slavers as we attempted to free them.  A particularily large slaver burst from a rough cottage beside a small stream and launched himself at us.  Aventari's two handed sword caught the beast squarly in the stomach and it doubled over.  Leaping forward I brought down my mace on its thick skull as I stabbed my sword into its muscular neck.  The beast roared in pain and anger, and blood seeped from the corner of its mouth, making its glistening fangs all the more angry looking.  Gracchus's chanting came to a roaring cresendo as a bolt of holy might swept into the beast, throwing it back against the cottage, and obviously breaking most of the creatures bones.  The slaver fell forwared, little more than a whimper came from its tooth-filled mouth as Aventari's sword delivered the final blow.  We found a small ring of keys, and began to free several slaves we encountered.  </p>
<p> We could see the flash of steel on the top of a rise at the centre of the valley and we proceeded up the side with caution.  At the top we found a large orc instructing several smaller ones apperently in the art of war.  To our trained eyes it was no more than a wood chopping lesson.  Several large trees behind the trainer provided perfect cover as we prepared to prevent any more orcs from wreaking havoc in the Faydark.  I climbed one of the trees and nocked my bow.  Both Gracchus and Aventari began to intone spells, and I let fly the arrow.  Death was not the desired effect of this shot, as it landed directly between the legs of the orc.  Looking down, comprehension finally dawned as my second arrow sliced through its left shoulder.  As my second arrow peirced the beast both Aventari's and Gracchus's spells went off.  The orcs feet were suddenly entwined and it was unable to move, as a bolt from the heavens blackened the blue hair on the beasts head.  I leaped from the tree as Aventari surged forward with his viscious sword.  Making short work of the unmoving trainer we turned on the stunned students.  To their credit some did actually stay and attempt to weild their crude weapons.  Others ran, they were not the fortunate ones.  Both Aventari and I immobilized the running orcs as we cleanly killed the fighting ones.  We kept the rooted orcs rooted for a while longer as we discussed in graphic detail what should be done, in orcish naturally.  </p>
<p> Moving quickly behind a low wall that led to the castle proper we attempted to enter the slave pens on the other side of the hill.  However much to our dismay these were too well guarded at this time.  We would need more man power to take such a large force.  We left this for another time. </p>
<p> We bandaged up what few wounds we had, and rested till we determined we were strong enough to enter the Castle proper. </p>
<p> Brodur, Ranger of Karana </p></td></tr>
  <tr><td ><a href='view_profile.asp?Action=Journal&Id=34284'>Return to Brodur's Journal</a></td></tr>
